# What is a Join?
A Join combines rows from two or more tables using a related column.

## Common Related Column:
```sql
customer_id
```

---

# Types of SQL Joins
- INNER JOIN
- LEFT JOIN
- RIGHT JOIN
- FULL JOIN
- CROSS JOIN
- SELF JOIN

---

# INNER JOIN

## Definition:
Returns only matching records from both tables.

## Syntax:
```sql
SELECT columns
FROM table1
INNER JOIN table2
ON table1.common_column = table2.common_column;
```

---

# Example:
```sql
SELECT customers.customer_name, orders.product_name, orders.amount
FROM customers
INNER JOIN orders
ON customers.customer_id = orders.customer_id;
```

---

# Result:
Only customers with matching orders are shown.

---

# LEFT JOIN

## Definition:
Returns all records from the left table and matching records from the right table.

If no match exists, NULL is returned.

---

# Example:
```sql
SELECT customers.customer_name, orders.product_name
FROM customers
LEFT JOIN orders
ON customers.customer_id = orders.customer_id;
```

---

# Result:
All customers appear, even if they have no orders.

---

# RIGHT JOIN

## Definition:
Returns all records from the right table and matching records from the left table.

---

# Example:
```sql
SELECT customers.customer_name, orders.product_name
FROM customers
RIGHT JOIN orders
ON customers.customer_id = orders.customer_id;
```

---

# Result:
All orders appear, even unmatched ones.

---

# FULL JOIN

## Definition:
Returns all records from both tables.

---

# Example:
```sql
SELECT customers.customer_name, orders.product_name
FROM customers
FULL JOIN orders
ON customers.customer_id = orders.customer_id;
```

---

# Result:
Includes matched + unmatched records from both tables.

---

# CROSS JOIN

## Definition:
Returns every possible combination of rows.

---

# Example:
```sql
SELECT customers.customer_name, orders.product_name
FROM customers
CROSS JOIN orders;
```

---

# Result:
Every customer paired with every order.

---

# SELF JOIN

## Definition:
A table joins with itself.

Used when records inside the same table are related.

---

# Example:
Employee-Manager Relationship:
```sql
SELECT A.name AS employee, B.name AS manager
FROM employees A
JOIN employees B
ON A.manager_id = B.employee_id;
```

---

# Visual Understanding

## INNER JOIN:
Matching only

## LEFT JOIN:
All left + matching right

## RIGHT JOIN:
All right + matching left

## FULL JOIN:
Everything

